00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:30.970
Now about Intelligentsia,
I'm curious like,

00:04:30.970 --> 00:04:33.280
what is the inspiration
behind Intelligentsia?

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:34.725
What does it mean,
like, what does

00:04:34.725 --> 00:04:35.982
it mean to specialty coffee?

00:04:35.982 --> 00:04:36.940
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: Yeah.

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:37.970
It's a great question.

00:04:37.970 --> 00:04:40.390
I think to answer it,
I want to go back.

00:04:40.390 --> 00:04:44.950
I mean, coffee is one of the
world's most widely traded

00:04:44.950 --> 00:04:45.850
commodities.

00:04:45.850 --> 00:04:51.260
And when Intelligentsia
was founded 23 years ago,

00:04:51.260 --> 00:04:54.100
this idea of specialty
coffee really didn't exist.

00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:56.335
I mean, there were people
that we're trying to do--

00:04:56.335 --> 00:04:57.460
well, I shouldn't say that.

00:04:57.460 --> 00:04:59.230
I mean, Peet's
and Starbucks were

00:04:59.230 --> 00:05:01.330
sort of the second
wave, what's commonly

00:05:01.330 --> 00:05:04.510
called the second wave
of coffee, the upgrade

00:05:04.510 --> 00:05:05.410
from Folgers.

00:05:05.410 --> 00:05:09.350
And when Intelligentsia
was founded 23 years ago,

00:05:09.350 --> 00:05:11.020
it was this idea
that, hey, coffee

00:05:11.020 --> 00:05:13.150
can actually be something more.

00:05:13.150 --> 00:05:16.330
We really need to treat
coffee as a culinary product,

00:05:16.330 --> 00:05:20.590
much more so than Starbucks
and Peet's were doing.

00:05:20.590 --> 00:05:23.710
And it became--

00:05:23.710 --> 00:05:25.840
I think what
Intelligentsia has always

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:28.180
stood for is this
idea that we want

00:05:28.180 --> 00:05:31.870
to keep the pristine ingredient
that comes from the farm as

00:05:31.870 --> 00:05:33.220
pure and as intact--

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:35.650
and present that
to our customers--

00:05:35.650 --> 00:05:36.250
as possible.

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:37.875
And that really gives
us an opportunity

00:05:37.875 --> 00:05:41.140
to showcase all the different
varietals and origins,

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:43.646
and all the different taste
characteristics that I know

00:05:43.646 --> 00:05:44.770
you're super familiar with.

00:05:44.770 --> 00:05:46.180
JOHN PETRENKO: Yeah.

00:05:46.180 --> 00:05:50.870
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: And you know,
one of the things that we truly

00:05:50.870 --> 00:05:52.730
believe is that we
have the opportunity

00:05:52.730 --> 00:05:56.924
to make change in the world
through extraordinary coffee.

00:05:56.924 --> 00:05:59.090
I mean, when we talk about
coffee at Intelligentsia,

00:05:59.090 --> 00:06:01.130
it is always
extraordinary coffee,

00:06:01.130 --> 00:06:04.700
because we are buying,
roasting, and serving

00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:06.390
the best coffee in the world.

00:06:06.390 --> 00:06:10.010
And we believe that really
through our trading model,

00:06:10.010 --> 00:06:12.410
the way that we buy
and sell coffees,

00:06:12.410 --> 00:06:16.010
we can have a huge impact on
the communities in countries

00:06:16.010 --> 00:06:20.000
all across the world and
give farmers an opportunity

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.600
to make a living and a
livelihood that is totally

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:26.120
disconnected from
that commodity market

00:06:26.120 --> 00:06:28.590
that I talked about
at the beginning.

00:06:28.590 --> 00:06:31.190
So I think, you know, it's
really about treating coffee

00:06:31.190 --> 00:06:34.280
as a culinary product that
carries through in, I think,

00:06:34.280 --> 00:06:35.270
everything that we do.

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:36.353
JOHN PETRENKO: Definitely.

00:06:36.353 --> 00:06:37.910
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN:
At our coffee bars,

00:06:37.910 --> 00:06:41.000
we were really at the
forefront of introducing

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.514
high design into coffee bars.

00:06:43.514 --> 00:06:45.680
If you go to our coffee
bars, everyone is different.

00:06:45.680 --> 00:06:49.310
We try to design coffee bars
for the specific neighborhood,

00:06:49.310 --> 00:06:52.910
and make it feel
like that customer--

00:06:52.910 --> 00:06:55.190
that's their coffee bar,
that's their Intelligentsia.

00:06:55.190 --> 00:06:58.010
It's not a cookie cutter model.

00:06:58.010 --> 00:07:00.837
And so all these
little details--

00:07:00.837 --> 00:07:03.170
you know, I like to say that
if a customer knows nothing

00:07:03.170 --> 00:07:06.140
about Intelligentsia and you
walk into one of our shops,

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:08.930
hopefully that customer stops
as soon as they cross the door

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:11.240
threshold and they say,
wait, something's different,

00:07:11.240 --> 00:07:13.460
this doesn't feel like
a common coffee shop.

00:07:13.460 --> 00:07:16.700
And that's something that
we want to have happen,

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:20.120
because we want to elevate the
coffee experience to something

00:07:20.120 --> 00:07:21.590
culinary.

00:07:21.590 --> 00:07:24.587
And it really carries through
to all the small details.

00:07:24.587 --> 00:07:27.170
We don't have any cups, but the
cups that we use in our shops,

00:07:27.170 --> 00:07:30.050
that was stuff that we
designed because we didn't like

00:07:30.050 --> 00:07:32.724
the way the cups felt in
our hands, the ones that

00:07:32.724 --> 00:07:33.890
were commonly on the market.

00:07:33.890 --> 00:07:36.389
So we designed one where you
had a place to rest your thumb.

00:07:36.389 --> 00:07:39.020
We designed the inside
so that you could easily

00:07:39.020 --> 00:07:40.160
pour latte art.

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:44.240
And again, the presentation was
something that was different.

00:07:44.240 --> 00:07:46.670
Another, I think, good
example is the menu

00:07:46.670 --> 00:07:48.260
that we print every
day at our shop.

00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:49.820
We get to pick the
coffees we serve,

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:52.230
and it's something different
each and every day.

00:07:52.230 --> 00:07:55.586
And it's this idea that, hey,
coffee is not just coffee.

00:07:55.586 --> 00:07:56.960
There's coffee
from Peru, there's

00:07:56.960 --> 00:07:59.480
coffee from El Salvador,
there's coffee from Rwanda.

00:07:59.480 --> 00:08:01.310
And then there's
50 different levels

00:08:01.310 --> 00:08:03.890
below that, that we're
just really starting

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:04.849
to scratch the surface.

00:08:04.849 --> 00:08:05.806
JOHN PETRENKO: Totally.

00:08:05.806 --> 00:08:07.730
I mean, and that leads
to my next question.

00:08:07.730 --> 00:08:10.970
And this is just like, a
coffee fanboy question.

00:08:10.970 --> 00:08:12.470
