00:10:50.220 --> 00:10:52.710
because I was living in
Guatemala for four years,

00:10:52.710 --> 00:10:54.706
and in South America
for five years,

00:10:54.706 --> 00:10:57.330
and I was leading projects with
thousands of smallholder coffee

00:10:57.330 --> 00:10:58.216
growers.

00:10:58.216 --> 00:11:00.090
One of the things that's
amazing about coffee

00:11:00.090 --> 00:11:02.610
from an impact perspective
or a development perspective,

00:11:02.610 --> 00:11:04.050
is that it's a
poor person's crop.

00:11:04.050 --> 00:11:06.600
It's primarily grown
by smallholder farmers

00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:08.790
who have maybe three,
or four, or five acres.

00:11:08.790 --> 00:11:10.740
So there's incredible
developmental potential

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:14.100
in coffee in general, and
specifically in our model.

00:11:14.100 --> 00:11:16.290
But that's why a development
agency was so deeply

00:11:16.290 --> 00:11:17.090
invested in coffee.

00:11:17.090 --> 00:11:18.840
But one of the nice
things about that work

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:21.090
was, it was kind of
like Switzerland.

00:11:21.090 --> 00:11:22.200
We were totally neutral.

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:24.062
And everybody in
the coffee industry

00:11:24.062 --> 00:11:26.520
is like, oh you're working on
coffee to make coffee better,

00:11:26.520 --> 00:11:28.800
more impactful for
smallholders, how can we help?

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:30.770
And so people would
fling open their doors.

00:11:30.770 --> 00:11:32.810
And I had over those 12
years, the opportunity

00:11:32.810 --> 00:11:36.870
to work with roasters
of all shapes and sizes.

00:11:36.870 --> 00:11:40.684
And I think that
Intelligentsia's sourcing

00:11:40.684 --> 00:11:43.350
program is awesome, but it's not
because I work for the company.

00:11:43.350 --> 00:11:45.475
I work for the company
because I think the sourcing

00:11:45.475 --> 00:11:47.270
program is awesome.

00:11:47.270 --> 00:11:49.320
As I did more and
more of that work

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:52.050
and I decided to make a
move to the private sector,

00:11:52.050 --> 00:11:53.550
there were really
very few companies

00:11:53.550 --> 00:11:55.740
that from a developmental
perspective were interesting.

00:11:55.740 --> 00:11:57.948
And Intelligentsia was really
at the top of the list.

00:11:57.948 --> 00:12:01.242
So we did get the questions
for this in advance,

00:12:01.242 --> 00:12:02.700
so I did get to
glance at it, and I

00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:04.800
made a long list of things
that make our sourcing program

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:05.350
awesome.

00:12:05.350 --> 00:12:07.940
I'm going to try to limit
myself to like four or five here

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:09.023
and just hit them quickly.

00:12:09.023 --> 00:12:11.430
But I could go down
to like 17 or 18 later

00:12:11.430 --> 00:12:15.210
if you're interested
after we break.

00:12:15.210 --> 00:12:17.230
The first thing I'll
say about our program

00:12:17.230 --> 00:12:20.320
is, our program is
called Direct Trade.

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:22.406
And it's language,
or it's a term that's

00:12:22.406 --> 00:12:24.780
used a lot in the industry
now, but really Intelligentsia

00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:26.960
developed the concept.

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:28.499
One of our colleagues,
Geoff Watts,

00:12:28.499 --> 00:12:30.540
was sort of the primary
intellectual and material

00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:31.374
author of the model.

00:12:31.374 --> 00:12:32.956
And the most important
part about that

00:12:32.956 --> 00:12:34.480
is, the direct part
of Direct Trade.

00:12:34.480 --> 00:12:36.250
And it's just what
it sounds like.

00:12:36.250 --> 00:12:39.090
We visit every one of our direct
trade partners every year,

00:12:39.090 --> 00:12:41.444
on their farms, in their
mills, and we work together

00:12:41.444 --> 00:12:43.860
to build the beautiful coffees
that we serve in our coffee

00:12:43.860 --> 00:12:46.350
bars and that you'll try today.

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:50.700
And from a sourcing
perspective, I

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:53.446
believe it's the most reliable
way to get great coffee.

00:12:53.446 --> 00:12:54.820
From a developmental
perspective,

00:12:54.820 --> 00:12:58.034
there's simply no
substitute for a situation

00:12:58.034 --> 00:13:00.450
in which a buyer is sitting
across the table from a grower

00:13:00.450 --> 00:13:02.530
and talking about what
they're going to do together,

00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:04.821
how we're going to create
quality, what kind of volumes

00:13:04.821 --> 00:13:07.830
we're going to work on
together this year, what

00:13:07.830 --> 00:13:09.630
are the specific
economic practices

00:13:09.630 --> 00:13:12.450
or post harvest practices
that can lead to quality.

00:13:12.450 --> 00:13:14.730
And there's just something
magical about that face

00:13:14.730 --> 00:13:16.530
to face contact.

00:13:16.530 --> 00:13:18.420
There are a lot of
certification programs

00:13:18.420 --> 00:13:23.490
out there, fair trade,
bird friendly, shade grown.

00:13:23.490 --> 00:13:24.480
They're all good.

00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:26.520
But for a lot of
people, that is a way

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:28.355
to outsource relationships.

00:13:28.355 --> 00:13:29.730
People do that
because they don't

00:13:29.730 --> 00:13:31.579
visit the farms every year.

00:13:31.579 --> 00:13:33.120
It's really fundamental
to our model,

00:13:33.120 --> 00:13:34.744
and it's the way that
we build quality.

00:13:34.744 --> 00:13:38.920
So the direct in direct
trade is important.

00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:40.950
The second thing
I'll say is, that's

00:13:40.950 --> 00:13:43.680
really important about
the program, is quality.

00:13:43.680 --> 00:13:46.880
We believe that-- as James
said, he mentioned the word

00:13:46.880 --> 00:13:48.660
culinary five or six times.

00:13:48.660 --> 00:13:50.580
It's such a bedrock
belief of ours,

00:13:50.580 --> 00:13:52.320
that coffee is a
culinary product.

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:55.065
And it is a commodity, but
not the coffee that we source,

00:13:55.065 --> 00:13:56.940
not the coffee that we
serve, and not the way

00:13:56.940 --> 00:13:57.900
we think about coffee.

00:13:57.900 --> 00:14:00.580
We think about coffee
as something elevated.

00:14:00.580 --> 00:14:03.070
It's a gastronomic
product, and the way

00:14:03.070 --> 00:14:05.310
we serve it is an
elevated process.

00:14:05.310 --> 00:14:08.010
And we build our partnerships
with that in mind.

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:10.340
We find people who share
our obsession with quality,

00:14:10.340 --> 00:14:13.970
and we build relationships
with them that last.

00:14:13.970 --> 00:14:17.060
For us, we think it's the most
important and effective way

00:14:17.060 --> 00:14:18.650
to be successful
in the marketplace.

00:14:18.650 --> 00:14:21.050
And it turns out, the same
thing is true for growers.

00:14:21.050 --> 00:14:23.520
The most reliable value
proposition for growers

00:14:23.520 --> 00:14:26.540
is to produce quality
year after year.

00:14:26.540 --> 00:14:29.950
The third thing is, the
way we trade coffee,

00:14:29.950 --> 00:14:31.255
or our commercial contracts.

00:14:31.255 --> 00:14:32.630
And in order to
understand what's

00:14:32.630 --> 00:14:34.835
special about the
way we do it, you

00:14:34.835 --> 00:14:36.710
need to understand a
little bit about the way

00:14:36.710 --> 00:14:37.850
the market normally works.

00:14:37.850 --> 00:14:39.516
And the market the
market normally works

00:14:39.516 --> 00:14:41.270
is, it's really intermediated.

00:14:41.270 --> 00:14:44.720
Coffee growers rarely
taste their own coffee.

00:14:44.720 --> 00:14:47.790
They almost never
meet coffee buyers.

00:14:47.790 --> 00:14:49.430
They'll sell their
coffee to someone

00:14:49.430 --> 00:14:51.170
in the town plaza,
who will maybe

00:14:51.170 --> 00:14:54.290
resell it to a miller,
who will then export it.

00:14:54.290 --> 00:14:58.340
And the two ends of
the chain don't meet.

00:14:58.340 --> 00:15:01.760
We build this model
directly with growers.

00:15:01.760 --> 00:15:04.190
And we build
incentives for quality.

00:15:04.190 --> 00:15:07.460
It's not just that we pay
more, we pay high prices,

00:15:07.460 --> 00:15:09.050
we pay stable prices.

00:15:09.050 --> 00:15:13.280
Normally the prices that growers
get, the market graph in coffee

00:15:13.280 --> 00:15:16.100
looks a little bit
like a seismograph

00:15:16.100 --> 00:15:17.156
or a polygraph test.

00:15:17.156 --> 00:15:19.280
It looks like this, and
it's very hard for a grower

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:22.040
to make a living with
prices that go up and down.

00:15:22.040 --> 00:15:24.157
We pay stable, high fixed
prices so that growers

00:15:24.157 --> 00:15:26.240
know what they're going
to make from us this year,

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:27.470
what they're going to make
next year, what they going

00:15:27.470 --> 00:15:28.772
to make the year after that.

00:15:28.772 --> 00:15:30.230
And the growers in
our supply chain

00:15:30.230 --> 00:15:34.160
have something that is a rare
and beautiful thing, which

00:15:34.160 --> 00:15:37.070
is the ability to make
plans for the future.

00:15:37.070 --> 00:15:40.290
And most growers are
not in that position.

00:15:40.290 --> 00:15:42.470
So I'm going to
stop there at three.

00:15:42.470 --> 00:15:46.100
I could go on, but there is one
more that I want to mention.

00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:47.570
It's called ECW.

00:15:47.570 --> 00:15:51.830
One of the amazing things for us
is that we work with some of--

00:15:51.830 --> 00:15:54.610
James said, we source and serve
the best coffees in the world.

00:15:54.610 --> 00:15:56.734
And we work with some of
the most celebrated coffee

00:15:56.734 --> 00:15:57.926
growers in the world.

00:15:57.926 --> 00:15:59.300
In 10 countries
around the world,

00:15:59.300 --> 00:16:00.924
there's a coffee
competition every year

00:16:00.924 --> 00:16:02.979
called the Cup of Excellence.

00:16:02.979 --> 00:16:04.520
And growers from
all over the country

00:16:04.520 --> 00:16:06.231
will submit samples
of their coffee.

00:16:06.231 --> 00:16:08.480
There is a national jury
that will go through it three

00:16:08.480 --> 00:16:10.100
or four times, and
they'll identify

00:16:10.100 --> 00:16:12.650
a small number of lots that
qualify for the final jury.

00:16:12.650 --> 00:16:15.150
And then international cuppers
come from all over the world,

00:16:15.150 --> 00:16:16.858
they sample the coffees,
they grade them,

00:16:16.858 --> 00:16:19.190
and then they're
sold at auction.

00:16:19.190 --> 00:16:22.160
We have like, a dozen different
Cup of Excellence winners

00:16:22.160 --> 00:16:23.280
in our supply network.

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:27.081
And we once a year get everybody
in our supply chain network

00:16:27.081 --> 00:16:29.330
together for an event we
call the Extraordinary Coffee

00:16:29.330 --> 00:16:30.260
Workshop.

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:33.566
We just did our 10th annual
one last month in Bolivia.

00:16:33.566 --> 00:16:35.690
And when you get there,
it's like the all-star game

00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:36.216
of coffee.

00:16:36.216 --> 00:16:38.090
It's like, people are
looking around the room

00:16:38.090 --> 00:16:41.150
and they're going, oh yeah, it's
you, I know about your coffee

00:16:41.150 --> 00:16:43.190
and you won Cup of
Excellence in Honduras,

00:16:43.190 --> 00:16:46.509
and you won Cup of
Excellence in Rwanda.

00:16:46.509 --> 00:16:48.300
And we've been doing
this now for 10 years.

00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:49.883
A lot of these people
are people we've

00:16:49.883 --> 00:16:52.430
traded with for 12 or 15 years.

00:16:52.430 --> 00:16:54.350
And they haven't just
become friends with us,

00:16:54.350 --> 00:16:56.580
but they've become
friends with one another.

00:16:56.580 --> 00:16:59.300
And so it's like, it's sort
of a part family reunion, part

00:16:59.300 --> 00:17:01.610
coffee geek week,
where we geek out

00:17:01.610 --> 00:17:04.470
on all the details of coffee
agronomy and processing,

00:17:04.470 --> 00:17:06.470
and try to find little
things that we can unlock

00:17:06.470 --> 00:17:08.520
to make our coffee better.

00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:11.150
And that level of transparency,
and that level of exchange

00:17:11.150 --> 00:17:13.822
where the best in the world
are learning from the best,

00:17:13.822 --> 00:17:16.280
and we're facilitating it, it's
something that just doesn't

00:17:16.280 --> 00:17:18.530
happen anywhere else in coffee.

00:17:18.530 --> 00:17:21.200
So that's one of the
most extraordinary things

00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:23.690
that Intelligentsia does.

00:17:23.690 --> 00:17:25.880
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: And if
I could just add, I mean,

00:17:25.880 --> 00:17:27.560
from the perspective
of a grower--

00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:31.470
because I was a grower
for a number of years--

00:17:31.470 --> 00:17:34.520
what Michael just described
probably doesn't sound that--

00:17:34.520 --> 00:17:37.084
like, it all make sense, right?

00:17:37.084 --> 00:17:39.000
You have a buyer sitting
across from a seller,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.650
they were paying prices based on
quality, that all kind of makes

00:17:42.650 --> 00:17:44.150
sense intuitively.

00:17:44.150 --> 00:17:47.450
But the point that
I want to emphasize,

00:17:47.450 --> 00:17:50.692
is that that 15 years
ago did not exist.

00:17:50.692 --> 00:17:51.650
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: Yeah.

00:17:51.650 --> 00:17:54.320
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: Everything--
as Michael said-- was traded--

00:17:54.320 --> 00:17:56.720
all coffee was really traded
through intermediaries.

00:17:56.720 --> 00:17:59.540
And so producers
really had no idea

00:17:59.540 --> 00:18:01.430
where their coffee
would end up going.

00:18:01.430 --> 00:18:03.830
And you had all
these intermediaries

00:18:03.830 --> 00:18:06.830
throughout the process that
were stepping on the product

00:18:06.830 --> 00:18:08.390
and making a little
bit of money.

00:18:08.390 --> 00:18:11.770
And really, the brilliance
of the Direct Trade model

00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:14.080
that Jeff really
thought about was,

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:17.120
we're going to cut all those
people out and push that value

00:18:17.120 --> 00:18:18.680
back to the producer.

00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:21.830
And that really changes
the game as a farmer,

00:18:21.830 --> 00:18:24.440
because you do have a partner
that you know is coming back

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:25.440
each and every year.

00:18:25.440 --> 00:18:27.264
And you can make smart
business decisions,

00:18:27.264 --> 00:18:29.180
you can start thinking
about it as a business.

00:18:29.180 --> 00:18:31.500
I'm going to save
up my money and I'm

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:32.750
going to build a new wet mill.

00:18:32.750 --> 00:18:34.730
Or I'm going to plant more land.

00:18:34.730 --> 00:18:35.840
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: Yeah.

00:18:35.840 --> 00:18:36.590
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: And
when you're really

00:18:36.590 --> 00:18:38.049
at the whim of the
commodity market

00:18:38.049 --> 00:18:39.464
and you don't know
if the price is

00:18:39.464 --> 00:18:40.940
going to be high
or low next year,

00:18:40.940 --> 00:18:42.470
you can't really run a business.

00:18:42.470 --> 00:18:45.957
You're really just trying to
scrape by and make a living.

00:18:45.957 --> 00:18:48.540
And I think-- you know, I know
that you know this really well.

00:18:48.540 --> 00:18:50.360
But it's one of
the best parts, I

00:18:50.360 --> 00:18:52.460
think, about working in
coffee, because you really

00:18:52.460 --> 00:18:57.320
do see the impact that our model
is having in these communities

00:18:57.320 --> 00:18:59.390
with these farmers.

00:18:59.390 --> 00:19:03.470
And you know, we carry that
through to the end consumer.

00:19:03.470 --> 00:19:08.420
We expect consumers to sort of
share in paying higher prices,

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:11.150
because we're paying higher
prices to the producers.

00:19:11.150 --> 00:19:17.600
But so far, consumers seem to be
willing to sort of step with us

00:19:17.600 --> 00:19:18.100
in this.

00:19:18.100 --> 00:19:20.039
So I think it's--

00:19:20.039 --> 00:19:21.830
some of this stuff
sounds really intuitive,

00:19:21.830 --> 00:19:24.380
but it's such a radical
departure for where

00:19:24.380 --> 00:19:26.000
coffee was 15 years ago.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:26.180
JOHN PETRENKO: Definitely.

00:19:26.180 --> 00:19:27.620
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: And
I think it's important,

00:19:27.620 --> 00:19:29.000
it wasn't just 15 years ago.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.480
I mean, most of coffee is
still traded that way today.

00:19:31.480 --> 00:19:31.790
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: That's true.

00:19:31.790 --> 00:19:33.748
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: And so
the developmental work

00:19:33.748 --> 00:19:36.890
that I was doing in the field in
southern Colombia, for example,

00:19:36.890 --> 00:19:39.927
with people who were coffee
growers for 30 years,

00:19:39.927 --> 00:19:41.760
and every year they'd
go and they'd harvest,

00:19:41.760 --> 00:19:43.550
they'd put the coffee on a
mule, and they'd take it down

00:19:43.550 --> 00:19:45.680
to the town plaza, and they'd
sell it for whatever price

00:19:45.680 --> 00:19:47.030
was written on the slate there.

00:19:47.030 --> 00:19:50.600
And nothing had changed, it had
been like that for generations.

00:19:50.600 --> 00:19:52.520
And then in that
context, I would

00:19:52.520 --> 00:19:53.754
come in and I would bring--

00:19:53.754 --> 00:19:55.670
when I was working for
the development agency,

00:19:55.670 --> 00:19:57.470
I brought
Intelligentsia with me.

00:19:57.470 --> 00:19:59.259
Just said, hey,
explain your model.

00:19:59.259 --> 00:20:00.800
Well, here's what
we would do, here's

00:20:00.800 --> 00:20:05.164
what we look for, here's how we
work, here's the prices we pay,

00:20:05.164 --> 00:20:06.830
here's the quality
requirements we have.

00:20:06.830 --> 00:20:10.590
It's not easy, you have to be
committed to quality with us.

00:20:10.590 --> 00:20:11.840
Is anybody interested in that?

00:20:11.840 --> 00:20:12.710
Everyone looked at
each other like,

00:20:12.710 --> 00:20:14.000
is that a trick
question, of course we're

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:14.791
interested in that.

00:20:14.791 --> 00:20:18.230
It's fundamentally revolutionary
in terms of that context.

00:20:18.230 --> 00:20:19.730
The other thing
that James mentioned

00:20:19.730 --> 00:20:22.430
is the idea of cutting
out the intermediaries.

00:20:22.430 --> 00:20:24.950
We still do, in some cases,
rely on intermediaries

00:20:24.950 --> 00:20:27.290
to do things like transport
the coffee for us.

00:20:27.290 --> 00:20:29.319
But the key point
is, that dialogue

00:20:29.319 --> 00:20:30.860
and getting back to
where it started,

00:20:30.860 --> 00:20:33.260
the idea of the direct
part of direct trade.

00:20:33.260 --> 00:20:35.900
If you think about a
traditional commodity chain,

00:20:35.900 --> 00:20:38.690
there may be six or
eight different actors

00:20:38.690 --> 00:20:41.660
between the coffee
bar and the grower.

00:20:41.660 --> 00:20:44.870
And the traditional model
is that those actors

00:20:44.870 --> 00:20:47.462
in the middle of the chain
make money off of the growers.

00:20:47.462 --> 00:20:49.670
We're trying to make money
together with the growers,

00:20:49.670 --> 00:20:51.500
and to be competitive
as a chain.

00:20:51.500 --> 00:20:57.237
But even in other chains where
there's a collaborative spirit,

00:20:57.237 --> 00:20:58.820
where there isn't
that direct contact,

00:20:58.820 --> 00:21:00.290
it's like a game of telephone.

00:21:00.290 --> 00:21:03.140
And you are all
educated people, you

00:21:03.140 --> 00:21:06.645
work for Google, you
share a world view.

00:21:06.645 --> 00:21:08.270
You share some aspects
of understanding

00:21:08.270 --> 00:21:09.230
how the world works.

00:21:09.230 --> 00:21:12.140
If we played a game of
telephone in here, our message,

00:21:12.140 --> 00:21:13.960
even a simple message
would break down.

00:21:13.960 --> 00:21:15.740
And if you think about
a supply chain that

00:21:15.740 --> 00:21:18.180
reaches across multiple
countries, multiple languages,

00:21:18.180 --> 00:21:21.350
different classes, it's very
hard to convey clear messages.

00:21:21.350 --> 00:21:23.014
And so us closing
the circle, and being

00:21:23.014 --> 00:21:25.430
able to sit down with the
grower and communicate directly,

00:21:25.430 --> 00:21:27.929
it's like for the grower,
it's like going into an exam

00:21:27.929 --> 00:21:29.220
with the answers ahead of time.

00:21:29.220 --> 00:21:31.120
They know exactly what the
market is demanding of them.

00:21:31.120 --> 00:21:33.536
There's no distortion of the
market's signal, it's direct,

00:21:33.536 --> 00:21:37.070
it's clear, and people can make
decisions and take decisions

00:21:37.070 --> 00:21:37.990
on the farm.

00:21:37.990 --> 00:21:40.140
They have much higher
probability of success.

00:21:40.140 --> 00:21:42.140
And that's the idea of
building quality together

00:21:42.140 --> 00:21:44.370
that's so revolutionary
about Intelligentsia.

00:21:44.370 --> 00:21:47.240
There are a lot of people
who serve quality coffee,

00:21:47.240 --> 00:21:49.427
but they're taking what
emerges from a process

00:21:49.427 --> 00:21:51.260
that they have no control
or influence over,

00:21:51.260 --> 00:21:53.390
whereas we're building
the coffees every year

00:21:53.390 --> 00:21:55.390
from the ground up,
beginning when the coffee is

00:21:55.390 --> 00:21:57.902
a seed and still on the plant.

00:21:57.902 --> 00:21:59.610
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: And
one last point, I--

00:21:59.610 --> 00:22:00.360
JOHN PETRENKO: Of course.

00:22:00.360 --> 00:22:01.520
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN:
But just to build

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:02.960
on something Michael
said, I think

00:22:02.960 --> 00:22:04.640
that the other piece
that's really important

00:22:04.640 --> 00:22:05.600
is the quality piece.

00:22:05.600 --> 00:22:10.040
Because it's easy for us to talk
and say, we can go to producers

00:22:10.040 --> 00:22:12.380
and say, here's our
quality expectations.

00:22:12.380 --> 00:22:15.980
But it's actually pretty hard to
meet our quality expectations.

00:22:15.980 --> 00:22:18.480
I think-- Sam can say
this better than--

00:22:18.480 --> 00:22:20.310
I don't know the stats as well.

00:22:20.310 --> 00:22:23.540
But I think we got
something like 3,000 samples

00:22:23.540 --> 00:22:26.540
that we received into our
lab to evaluate and decide

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:28.220
whether we're going
to buy or not.

00:22:28.220 --> 00:22:32.360
We select like 1% of
those to actually buy.

00:22:32.360 --> 00:22:35.030
So it's not easy to
make the cut, which

00:22:35.030 --> 00:22:37.940
is I think, your point
about the all-star team.

00:22:37.940 --> 00:22:41.810
But we're committed
partners with the producers.

00:22:41.810 --> 00:22:46.100
And so it often takes us
four to five years working

00:22:46.100 --> 00:22:48.810
with a producer and saying,
look, we believe in you,

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:51.680
you have the right
characteristics that we found

00:22:51.680 --> 00:22:53.330
for you to be
successful, we're going

00:22:53.330 --> 00:22:57.080
to help train you on how
you produce quality coffee.

00:22:57.080 --> 00:22:58.790
And often it takes
four or five years

00:22:58.790 --> 00:23:01.310
before we'll actually
get a container of coffee

00:23:01.310 --> 00:23:02.870
that we buy.

00:23:02.870 --> 00:23:05.330
But it's something that,
again, this idea that we're

00:23:05.330 --> 00:23:08.030
partners with the producers.

00:23:08.030 --> 00:23:11.060
And the quality
road is not easy.

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:12.660
JOHN PETRENKO: Right on, nice.

00:23:12.660 --> 00:23:14.927
Well, next question I have
is going to be for Sam.

00:23:14.927 --> 00:23:17.510
I'm very curious on like, what
do you look for in the roasting

00:23:17.510 --> 00:23:18.010
process?

00:23:18.010 --> 00:23:20.090
What's your philosophy
in roasting and quality

00:23:20.090 --> 00:23:21.560
control with Intelligentsia?

00:23:21.560 --> 00:23:24.870
And follow up, what is your
favorite coffee to roast?

00:23:24.870 --> 00:23:25.775
SAM SABORI: OK.

00:23:25.775 --> 00:23:29.600
You know, we've echoed it a
few times, but the sentiment

00:23:29.600 --> 00:23:31.520
that it's actually--

00:23:31.520 --> 00:23:35.030
you approach it as if it's
any other piece of food.

00:23:35.030 --> 00:23:37.920
You want to stabilize all your
variables first and foremost,

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:40.580
and that's where this Direct
Trade model comes through.

00:23:40.580 --> 00:23:42.200
And I'm sure we'll
talk about it more,

00:23:42.200 --> 00:23:45.849
but just having that streamlined
communication between ourselves

00:23:45.849 --> 00:23:47.390
and the farmer to
actually understand

00:23:47.390 --> 00:23:50.060
what's going on in the
growing conditions,

00:23:50.060 --> 00:23:51.800
going on on the farm.

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:55.340
I think that's key in
playing a fundamental role

00:23:55.340 --> 00:23:57.440
in a great roast.

00:23:57.440 --> 00:23:59.930
As far as the
actual roast, for us

00:23:59.930 --> 00:24:02.030
it goes anywhere from
10 to 15 minutes.

00:24:02.030 --> 00:24:06.995
We're stabilizing variables
as often as possible.

00:24:06.995 --> 00:24:09.707
There are some roasters,
some have a philosophy

00:24:09.707 --> 00:24:12.040
that you want to smell the
coffee as you're roasting it,

00:24:12.040 --> 00:24:15.280
you want to take
visual observations.

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:17.950
For us, we found
that the roast goes

00:24:17.950 --> 00:24:21.730
so fast, it's really hard to
actually consistently say,

00:24:21.730 --> 00:24:26.680
that's the color, whatever we
want from an actual numbers

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:28.360
perspective.

00:24:28.360 --> 00:24:30.190
Because the way we
will roast, is we'll

00:24:30.190 --> 00:24:33.760
roast our coffees to a
specific number on the Maillard

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:34.540
reaction.

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:37.750
So depending on
how brown it is, we

00:24:37.750 --> 00:24:40.990
are going to roast that
to say, 55 or a 60.

00:24:40.990 --> 00:24:45.460
And we have specific parameters
for each coffee that we want.

00:24:45.460 --> 00:24:50.170
As far as the overall big
picture view for roasting,

00:24:50.170 --> 00:24:51.879
we want a lot of
momentum on our coffees.

00:24:51.879 --> 00:24:53.294
We want to roast
them efficiently,

00:24:53.294 --> 00:24:54.700
and we want to roast them clean.

00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:57.010
If we run them too
slow, it's kind

00:24:57.010 --> 00:24:58.540
of like putting
an egg on a frying

00:24:58.540 --> 00:25:00.110
pan that hasn't
been preheated, it

00:25:00.110 --> 00:25:02.950
just kind of becomes kind of--

00:25:02.950 --> 00:25:04.660
you don't get that
sizzle, you know?

00:25:04.660 --> 00:25:09.376
It just kind of sits there, it's
flabby, you know you messed up.

00:25:09.376 --> 00:25:11.500
So for us, we want to make
sure with that momentum,

00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:14.260
we can push our coffees
as quickly as possible

00:25:14.260 --> 00:25:16.280
with continual
reduction and heat.

00:25:16.280 --> 00:25:17.642
I don't know if that's--

00:25:17.642 --> 00:25:18.475
JOHN PETRENKO: Yeah.

00:25:18.475 --> 00:25:18.970
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: Your
favorite to roast.

00:25:18.970 --> 00:25:21.030
SAM SABORI: That's about as
distilled as I can make it.

00:25:21.030 --> 00:25:21.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:21.480 --> 00:25:22.830
JOHN PETRENKO: All
right, definitely.

00:25:22.830 --> 00:25:23.920
And then favorite to roast?

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:24.760
SAM SABORI: Favorite to roast?

00:25:24.760 --> 00:25:25.720
It'd probably be Kenya.

00:25:25.720 --> 00:25:26.470
That's probably why it's--

00:25:26.470 --> 00:25:27.303
JOHN PETRENKO: Yeah?

00:25:27.303 --> 00:25:29.320
Like a peaberry
or just kind of--

00:25:29.320 --> 00:25:30.940
SAM SABORI: Probably the AAs.

00:25:30.940 --> 00:25:35.050
So a Kenyan coffee,
they're classified

00:25:35.050 --> 00:25:37.990
based on their screen
size, so based on how big

00:25:37.990 --> 00:25:39.730
or small each bean is.

00:25:39.730 --> 00:25:45.280
And each grade as it goes
from AB to AA, AB or AA,

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:50.020
or lower grades, they just
continue to get refined.

00:25:50.020 --> 00:25:55.630
So the AA, say that's one of
the better milling constructions

00:25:55.630 --> 00:25:58.180
that we can get, that
allows us to be a lot more

00:25:58.180 --> 00:26:00.670
direct with our approach.

00:26:00.670 --> 00:26:02.920
And it allows us to kind of
push the coffees further.

00:26:02.920 --> 00:26:06.130
Whereas if say we were
roasting a coffee that's

00:26:06.130 --> 00:26:09.390
borderline specialty,
say not from Kenya,

00:26:09.390 --> 00:26:11.140
we might have to adjust
our roast approach

00:26:11.140 --> 00:26:12.760
to slow down or speed up.

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:14.950
Because if we roast
it at any other level,

00:26:14.950 --> 00:26:16.720
we're going to
get vegetal notes,

00:26:16.720 --> 00:26:20.302
we're going to get sour notes,
we're going to get astringency.

00:26:20.302 --> 00:26:22.510
So a lot of times when you're
tasting a coffee that's

00:26:22.510 --> 00:26:25.030
borderline specialty,
the roaster

00:26:25.030 --> 00:26:28.240
is making a decision to take it
that far because he's actually

00:26:28.240 --> 00:26:29.950
trying to minimize
the negatives.

00:26:29.950 --> 00:26:31.600
Whereas with a
Kenyan coffee, you

00:26:31.600 --> 00:26:34.540
can kind of keep
pushing them to continue

00:26:34.540 --> 00:26:36.216
to expand the complexity.

00:26:36.216 --> 00:26:37.050
JOHN PETRENKO: OK.

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:38.784
Very cool.

