00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:06.990
So one thing is like, with
climate change affecting

00:29:06.990 --> 00:29:10.450
crop production and farming
all across the world,

00:29:10.450 --> 00:29:12.780
how do you see coffee being
affected by this crisis?

00:29:12.780 --> 00:29:14.550
And how do you see
coffee going forward

00:29:14.550 --> 00:29:15.883
if these trends aren't reversed?

00:29:19.302 --> 00:29:20.260
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: Yeah.

00:29:20.260 --> 00:29:27.980
So climate change is a big deal
in every aspect of our lives,

00:29:27.980 --> 00:29:30.420
and coffee is no exception.

00:29:30.420 --> 00:29:31.550
Climate change is--

00:29:33.941 --> 00:29:35.940
I've heard coffee described,
I think accurately,

00:29:35.940 --> 00:29:37.650
as a Goldilocks crop.

00:29:37.650 --> 00:29:39.210
Can't be too hot,
it can be too cold.

00:29:39.210 --> 00:29:40.140
It has to be just right.

00:29:40.140 --> 00:29:42.515
It can't have too much rain,
it can have too little rain.

00:29:42.515 --> 00:29:44.400
It has to have just the
right amount of rain.

00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:47.420
Arabica coffee, which
is what we source,

00:29:47.420 --> 00:29:51.120
the specialty coffee is
almost entirely Arabica.

00:29:51.120 --> 00:29:53.490
It's a very finicky crop.

00:29:53.490 --> 00:29:56.850
And it grows in the tropics
at a certain elevation range,

00:29:56.850 --> 00:29:59.730
and has these requirements
for temperature and rain.

00:29:59.730 --> 00:30:03.636
And those are getting
changed with climate change.

00:30:03.636 --> 00:30:05.760
And I think there's been
a lot of research on this,

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:10.320
and general tendency
that people see in coffee

00:30:10.320 --> 00:30:13.410
is that the optimal elevation
for coffee, the elevation

00:30:13.410 --> 00:30:15.810
range for coffee is rising
as temperatures rise.

00:30:15.810 --> 00:30:17.717
So coffee likes the cool.

00:30:17.717 --> 00:30:19.800
One of the things we look
at when we source coffee

00:30:19.800 --> 00:30:22.710
is the diurnal temperature
range, so the difference

00:30:22.710 --> 00:30:26.169
between the high in the
midday and the low at night.

00:30:26.169 --> 00:30:27.960
And the cool temperatures
stress the plant,

00:30:27.960 --> 00:30:29.670
and they contribute
to the creation

00:30:29.670 --> 00:30:31.940
of these beautiful
complex flavors.

00:30:31.940 --> 00:30:34.080
And that cool, to get
that kind of cool,

00:30:34.080 --> 00:30:35.500
you have to go
higher and higher.

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:36.990
And we know because of
the nature of mountains,

00:30:36.990 --> 00:30:38.910
the higher you go, the
less land is available.

00:30:38.910 --> 00:30:43.620
So coffee lands are going away
under a kind of a business

00:30:43.620 --> 00:30:45.765
as usual scenario.

00:30:45.765 --> 00:30:47.640
And there's very little
that a grower can do.

00:30:47.640 --> 00:30:50.670
Growers can mitigate the effects
of that and sort of forestall

00:30:50.670 --> 00:30:53.310
that through their management
practices by managing shade

00:30:53.310 --> 00:30:55.680
more intensively, lowering
the ambient temperature

00:30:55.680 --> 00:30:57.150
of their coffee groves.

00:30:57.150 --> 00:30:58.560
But ultimately,
they're not going

00:30:58.560 --> 00:31:00.184
to be able to make
the kinds of changes

00:31:00.184 --> 00:31:02.830
on the farm to keep up
with climate change.

00:31:02.830 --> 00:31:06.000
So one of the very
important short term things

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:08.340
is working with
growers to implement

00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:10.410
some of those things that
will help to optimize

00:31:10.410 --> 00:31:12.490
the quality of their coffee.

00:31:12.490 --> 00:31:16.000
But the long term, we
require more research.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:19.380
So all the staple
crops that we consume,

00:31:19.380 --> 00:31:21.780
rice, and corn,
and wheat, they all

00:31:21.780 --> 00:31:23.650
have publicly funded
research institutes.

00:31:23.650 --> 00:31:26.700
But coffee as a
cash crop does not.

00:31:26.700 --> 00:31:28.890
And so the industry has
been working together

00:31:28.890 --> 00:31:30.570
over the last 5 to
10 years to create

00:31:30.570 --> 00:31:33.660
a collective research--
an industry driven

00:31:33.660 --> 00:31:35.700
research agency.

00:31:35.700 --> 00:31:40.140
They're looking for sort
of the holy grail, which

00:31:40.140 --> 00:31:46.910
is a combination of varieties
that resist drought and disease

00:31:46.910 --> 00:31:48.900
and they produce a
beautiful flavor in the cup.

00:31:48.900 --> 00:31:52.140
Generally plant breeders are
just focused on productivity,

00:31:52.140 --> 00:31:55.460
they want to maximize yield and
they don't think about flavor.

00:31:55.460 --> 00:31:57.000
There's an
organization that we've

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:58.560
been supporting
since its inception,

00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:00.390
since it was just in
the concept phase,

00:32:00.390 --> 00:32:02.400
it's called World
Coffee Research.

00:32:02.400 --> 00:32:05.400
And this is their
pursuit, to make

00:32:05.400 --> 00:32:08.250
specialty coffee viable in
an era of accelerated climate

00:32:08.250 --> 00:32:09.210
change.

00:32:09.210 --> 00:32:12.030
And they're doing-- they've done
more in the last 5 to 10 years

00:32:12.030 --> 00:32:13.764
on plant breeding
through partnerships

00:32:13.764 --> 00:32:15.180
with the local
research institutes

00:32:15.180 --> 00:32:16.800
throughout the
coffee growing world

00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:18.892
than has been done in
the history of specialty

00:32:18.892 --> 00:32:19.600
leading up to it.

00:32:19.600 --> 00:32:23.730
And we contribute, we consider
it part of our cost of goods.

00:32:23.730 --> 00:32:27.630
We contribute a half a penny per
pound for every pound of coffee

00:32:27.630 --> 00:32:30.180
that we buy to
this research fund.

00:32:30.180 --> 00:32:33.650
James sits on the board as
another part of our belief in

00:32:33.650 --> 00:32:35.675
and commitment to this effort.

00:32:35.675 --> 00:32:37.291
And it's fundamental.

00:32:37.291 --> 00:32:38.790
But it's definitely
changing things,

00:32:38.790 --> 00:32:41.700
and it is changing the
patterns of disease,

00:32:41.700 --> 00:32:43.980
changing cup profile.

00:32:43.980 --> 00:32:45.780
And it's changing so fast that--

00:32:45.780 --> 00:32:48.746
we're so deeply engaged
with our partners

00:32:48.746 --> 00:32:50.370
on the coffees that
come in every year,

00:32:50.370 --> 00:32:52.759
and we're cupping them
throughout their life span.

00:32:52.759 --> 00:32:54.300
And so we're working
to give feedback

00:32:54.300 --> 00:32:57.990
and trying to see what the
changes are in the cup.

00:32:57.990 --> 00:33:01.140
We're continuing to
source amazing coffees,

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:02.880
but it's something
that everybody

00:33:02.880 --> 00:33:06.150
in every aspect, every step in
the supply chain is working on.

00:33:06.150 --> 00:33:08.580
So we're funding research,
we're working at the farm level

00:33:08.580 --> 00:33:09.246
to deal with it.

00:33:09.246 --> 00:33:11.820
We're trying to promote
water saving technologies.

00:33:11.820 --> 00:33:14.100
But it's a challenge
in coffee as it

00:33:14.100 --> 00:33:17.797
is in all of agriculture and
every human endeavor really.

00:33:17.797 --> 00:33:18.630
JOHN PETRENKO: Yeah.

00:33:18.630 --> 00:33:19.588
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: Yeah.

00:33:19.588 --> 00:33:22.110
I mean, just two
specific examples.

00:33:22.110 --> 00:33:26.550
Where I was living in
Brazil, that region just

00:33:26.550 --> 00:33:29.230
came out of the worst drought.

00:33:29.230 --> 00:33:31.470
They were in a two year drought.

00:33:31.470 --> 00:33:35.580
And many, many producers
in the region where I was

00:33:35.580 --> 00:33:39.420
have abandoned their farms,
because the coffee trees died.

00:33:39.420 --> 00:33:42.990
And given that most
of these producers

00:33:42.990 --> 00:33:44.760
aren't focused on
quality, there's

00:33:44.760 --> 00:33:46.800
really no future for them.

00:33:46.800 --> 00:33:51.080
So given that it is
mostly a smallholder crop,

00:33:51.080 --> 00:33:55.020
it's a huge risk to the
industry as a whole.

00:33:55.020 --> 00:33:57.050
The other example was,
as Michael mentioned,

00:33:57.050 --> 00:34:00.530
the other problem with
climate change is disease.

00:34:00.530 --> 00:34:04.107
Five years ago, four years
ago, Central America--

00:34:04.107 --> 00:34:05.690
all the countries
in Central America--

00:34:05.690 --> 00:34:09.949
had an outbreak of a disease
called leaf rust, and really

00:34:09.949 --> 00:34:14.270
devastated Guatemala,
Honduras, El Salvador,

00:34:14.270 --> 00:34:16.820
and wiped out many, many farms.

00:34:16.820 --> 00:34:19.580
And it's really a product
of higher temperatures

00:34:19.580 --> 00:34:25.040
allows this fungus to
breed more rapidly.

00:34:25.040 --> 00:34:28.070
And as Michael mentioned,
the future really

00:34:28.070 --> 00:34:30.800
is in plant breeding
and figuring out

00:34:30.800 --> 00:34:32.690
how to create the
super plant that

00:34:32.690 --> 00:34:37.100
can produce higher quality,
resist disease, resist higher

00:34:37.100 --> 00:34:38.330
temperatures.

00:34:38.330 --> 00:34:41.750
But frankly, as an industry,
we're pretty far behind

00:34:41.750 --> 00:34:43.489
in terms of that research.

00:34:43.489 --> 00:34:46.679
And we're-- there's a lot of
pressure to catch up quickly.

00:34:46.679 --> 00:34:48.179
JOHN PETRENKO: I
think we don't need

00:34:48.179 --> 00:34:50.575
argue that technology
and the internet

00:34:50.575 --> 00:34:52.699
has been pretty disruptive
in the past two decades.

00:34:52.699 --> 00:34:55.749
How has it changed
for your business?

00:34:55.749 --> 00:34:57.540
That and like, social
media and everything.

00:34:57.540 --> 00:34:58.498
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: Yeah.

00:34:58.498 --> 00:34:59.347
JOHN PETRENKO: Yeah.

00:34:59.347 --> 00:35:00.930
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN:
So I'm going to take

00:35:00.930 --> 00:35:02.060
this in a couple
different directions.

00:35:02.060 --> 00:35:02.570
JOHN PETRENKO: Great.

00:35:02.570 --> 00:35:04.840
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: The first
I think is, in some ways,

00:35:04.840 --> 00:35:07.900
I think coffee
hasn't changed much.

00:35:07.900 --> 00:35:10.680
I mean, if you look at the
roasters that we use today,

00:35:10.680 --> 00:35:14.459
they're the same roasters that
we've used 80, 90 years ago.

00:35:14.459 --> 00:35:16.000
There's some upgrades
here and there.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:18.900
But overall, it's like you
apply heat to this metal drum,

00:35:18.900 --> 00:35:22.200
you put green coffee
in, and it turns brown.

00:35:22.200 --> 00:35:24.810
So in some ways, I
think there's frankly

00:35:24.810 --> 00:35:27.810
a huge opportunity
for the industry

00:35:27.810 --> 00:35:29.280
to kind of catch
up and figure out,

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:31.170
are there other ways
to make coffee--

00:35:31.170 --> 00:35:33.150
to turn coffee brown?

00:35:33.150 --> 00:35:35.940
So that's point number one.

00:35:35.940 --> 00:35:38.080
There's pretty cool stuff
that's happening though,

00:35:38.080 --> 00:35:41.790
in terms of the
ability to produce

00:35:41.790 --> 00:35:45.780
great tasting cups of coffee
where it doesn't require

00:35:45.780 --> 00:35:47.526
a lot of manual work.

00:35:47.526 --> 00:35:49.650
I mean, one of the things
that we always talk about

00:35:49.650 --> 00:35:52.380
is, when you think about all
the different people that touch

00:35:52.380 --> 00:35:55.830
coffee in the supply chain;
from the producer, their choices

00:35:55.830 --> 00:35:57.750
in the varietal;
the picker, they

00:35:57.750 --> 00:36:00.450
choose which cherries they're
going to put in the bill--

00:36:00.450 --> 00:36:04.260
in the bag; the
miller, the wet mill,

00:36:04.260 --> 00:36:08.712
the dry mill; the roaster;
the barista; the end user.

00:36:08.712 --> 00:36:10.170
I mean, there's so
many people that

00:36:10.170 --> 00:36:13.830
can affect how a cup
of coffee tastes.

00:36:13.830 --> 00:36:15.670
And we really--

00:36:15.670 --> 00:36:18.810
I think where we are going
to go as an industry, where

00:36:18.810 --> 00:36:21.000
this industry is
going is, that's

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:22.454
going to get whittled down.

00:36:22.454 --> 00:36:24.870
Frankly we have too many people
that can affect the flavor

00:36:24.870 --> 00:36:26.575
and not really optimize it.

00:36:26.575 --> 00:36:28.950
And I think what we're going
to see over the next 5 or 10

00:36:28.950 --> 00:36:32.760
years is, the number
of people that--

00:36:32.760 --> 00:36:35.910
we're going to get coffee
into consumers' hands

00:36:35.910 --> 00:36:39.090
in a finished good
kind of way that

00:36:39.090 --> 00:36:42.450
actually tastes
amazing in a better way

00:36:42.450 --> 00:36:43.470
than we do currently.

00:36:43.470 --> 00:36:45.420
Selling a consumer
a bag of coffee

00:36:45.420 --> 00:36:46.620
is always terrifying for us.

00:36:46.620 --> 00:36:51.900
Because they take it home,
they put it in their grinder,

00:36:51.900 --> 00:36:56.759
they add too much water, they
don't do 18.25 to 1 ratio.

00:36:56.759 --> 00:36:58.800
And then they look at the
bag and they say, gosh,

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:00.845
why does Intelligentsia
coffee not taste great?

00:37:00.845 --> 00:37:02.220
And it's like,
no, but you didn't

00:37:02.220 --> 00:37:04.960
do all these different things.

00:37:04.960 --> 00:37:08.580
So I think there's-- from
a technology standpoint,

00:37:08.580 --> 00:37:10.170
I think there's
more from a brewing,

00:37:10.170 --> 00:37:13.990
roasting perspective that
is starting to happen,

00:37:13.990 --> 00:37:18.360
but hasn't really happened--
hasn't caught up yet.

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:20.337
I was in Brazil--

00:37:20.337 --> 00:37:22.420
I still buy coffee for
Brazil for Intelligentsia--

00:37:22.420 --> 00:37:26.070
and I was on this farm, and
they actually grow grapes there.

00:37:26.070 --> 00:37:30.060
And they have a-- they're
starting a winery.

00:37:30.060 --> 00:37:33.510
And so we took a day's
picking of coffee

00:37:33.510 --> 00:37:37.170
and we took it to the winery and
we used the winery's equipment

00:37:37.170 --> 00:37:38.880
to process the coffee.

00:37:38.880 --> 00:37:43.020
Like super precise,
super detailed.

00:37:43.020 --> 00:37:46.410
We had this trained
professional, wine professional

00:37:46.410 --> 00:37:48.480
there consulting with us.

00:37:48.480 --> 00:37:50.790
And you don't see
that in coffee today,

00:37:50.790 --> 00:37:53.970
it's still pretty random
and haphazard on the farm.

00:37:53.970 --> 00:37:56.310
So I think there's
a lot of opportunity

00:37:56.310 --> 00:38:01.260
in terms of being more precise
throughout the whole supply

00:38:01.260 --> 00:38:01.960
chain.

00:38:01.960 --> 00:38:04.990
I think to get to
your second question,

00:38:04.990 --> 00:38:07.380
the great thing about social
media and the internet

00:38:07.380 --> 00:38:11.160
is that it's given
voices to smaller brands

00:38:11.160 --> 00:38:12.930
like Intelligentsia,
where we can actually

00:38:12.930 --> 00:38:18.450
reach more people in a way that
we couldn't have 20 years ago.

00:38:18.450 --> 00:38:21.750
And education is one of
the most important things

00:38:21.750 --> 00:38:22.740
for a company like us.

00:38:22.740 --> 00:38:26.310
Why do you pay $22 for
a bag of Tikur Anbessa

00:38:26.310 --> 00:38:29.730
from Ethiopia when
there's a bag of Starbucks

00:38:29.730 --> 00:38:31.990
at the grocery store for $7?

00:38:31.990 --> 00:38:33.960
So what is different
about Intelligentsia

00:38:33.960 --> 00:38:37.430
from Starbucks, it's both
brown beans in a bag?

00:38:37.430 --> 00:38:40.830
And it really gives us a
chance to educate consumers

00:38:40.830 --> 00:38:43.560
about all the things we've
been talking about today.

00:38:43.560 --> 00:38:45.420
That, and then also
educate consumers

00:38:45.420 --> 00:38:48.180
about how to brew the cup
of coffee so it tastes good.

00:38:48.180 --> 00:38:50.220
JOHN PETRENKO:
Definitely, definitely.

00:38:50.220 --> 00:38:54.177
One kind of fanboy
question I have is,

00:38:54.177 --> 00:38:55.260
you guys go out to origin.

00:38:55.260 --> 00:38:57.450
It's something I've always
really dreamed of doing,

00:38:57.450 --> 00:38:59.320
I think it would be amazing.

00:38:59.320 --> 00:39:02.040
I'm curious, what are your
favorite trips of origin

00:39:02.040 --> 00:39:05.010
to go to, and maybe like
a fun crazy story that

00:39:05.010 --> 00:39:06.440
has happened while at origin?

00:39:06.440 --> 00:39:07.370
That's for all three of you.

00:39:07.370 --> 00:39:09.036
SAM SABORI: I think
you've got this one.

00:39:09.036 --> 00:39:10.545
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:11.179 --> 00:39:13.804
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: I think I know
the story you want me to tell.

00:39:13.804 --> 00:39:14.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:14.770 --> 00:39:17.430
It's not always fun stuff
that happens at origin.

00:39:17.430 --> 00:39:21.330
Sometimes crazy stuff happens
that's not entirely fun.

00:39:21.330 --> 00:39:22.620
Well I think it's--

00:39:22.620 --> 00:39:26.710
certainly it's like, there's
kind of this thing in coffee,

00:39:26.710 --> 00:39:28.920
and not everybody falls
into the same pattern.

00:39:28.920 --> 00:39:33.490
But the principle entry point
for coffee is as a barista.

00:39:33.490 --> 00:39:36.690
Like you just heard Sam's
experience, it's pretty common.

00:39:36.690 --> 00:39:38.792
People when they--
they're a barista,

00:39:38.792 --> 00:39:41.250
and if it's just that they want
benefits and pay for school

00:39:41.250 --> 00:39:42.160
and they're out, there out.

00:39:42.160 --> 00:39:43.320
But a lot of people
catch the bug

00:39:43.320 --> 00:39:45.750
and they get totally passionate
about this thing that's

00:39:45.750 --> 00:39:47.940
endlessly complex and
really fascinating, way

00:39:47.940 --> 00:39:50.481
more interesting than they ever
thought it was when they were

00:39:50.481 --> 00:39:51.936
just trying to pay some bills.

00:39:51.936 --> 00:39:53.310
And they go down
the rabbit hole.

00:39:53.310 --> 00:39:55.320
And generally, the
more people get

00:39:55.320 --> 00:39:57.890
interested in coffee, the more
they get interested in where

00:39:57.890 --> 00:39:59.640
it comes from, and the
people who grow it,

00:39:59.640 --> 00:40:00.931
and they want to get to origin.

00:40:00.931 --> 00:40:03.840
And so there's something kind
of mythical about getting

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:05.340
to take your first origin trip.

00:40:05.340 --> 00:40:08.550
It's sort of like a milestone
in the professional development

00:40:08.550 --> 00:40:10.770
of serious coffee people.

00:40:10.770 --> 00:40:13.900
And so there's no question,
it's the highlight of the job.

00:40:13.900 --> 00:40:16.650
All three of us here
buy coffee in addition

00:40:16.650 --> 00:40:18.412
to the work we do
at the roasting

00:40:18.412 --> 00:40:19.870
works a couple of
blocks from here.

00:40:19.870 --> 00:40:22.810
So the trips are things
we look forward to.

00:40:22.810 --> 00:40:25.170
And we take at least one a
year, sometimes more than one

00:40:25.170 --> 00:40:27.600
when we have a special
project going on.

00:40:27.600 --> 00:40:29.190
And we look forward to it.

00:40:29.190 --> 00:40:32.640
And it's a time when
you cut through all

00:40:32.640 --> 00:40:35.250
the emails and the phone calls,
and you just sit on the farm.

00:40:35.250 --> 00:40:38.580
And there just something magical
about being on a coffee farm.

00:40:38.580 --> 00:40:41.430
I particularly love
shade grown coffee,

00:40:41.430 --> 00:40:43.200
where you're outside
in the tropical sun

00:40:43.200 --> 00:40:46.140
and it's hot, maybe 70 degrees,
but a really strong sun.

00:40:46.140 --> 00:40:48.060
And you step into
the coffee grove

00:40:48.060 --> 00:40:50.550
and the temperature drops like
12 degrees, and it's cool,

00:40:50.550 --> 00:40:53.070
and you feel the moisture,
and you understand what

00:40:53.070 --> 00:40:55.170
the shade does for the coffee.

00:40:55.170 --> 00:40:58.955
And then you're doing it
together with a grower,

00:40:58.955 --> 00:40:59.580
and it's great.

00:40:59.580 --> 00:41:01.590
And there's a lot of
planning that goes into it.

00:41:01.590 --> 00:41:02.670
You talk about, hey,
here's what we'd

00:41:02.670 --> 00:41:03.630
like to do together this year.

00:41:03.630 --> 00:41:05.970
Last year we bought this much,
we'd like to buy a little more,

00:41:05.970 --> 00:41:07.140
we'd like to buy a
little less, we'd

00:41:07.140 --> 00:41:09.250
like it to be more like
this, or less like that.

00:41:09.250 --> 00:41:11.640
So you do all this
planning and then you go

00:41:11.640 --> 00:41:14.190
and you're on the farm
together, you're at the mill

00:41:14.190 --> 00:41:17.592
together putting
in place the plan.

00:41:17.592 --> 00:41:19.050
What they want me
to talk about is,

00:41:19.050 --> 00:41:20.330
last year we did
all this planning.

00:41:20.330 --> 00:41:20.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:20.830 --> 00:41:23.924
I made my first trip as the
new coffee buyer in Bolivia.

00:41:23.924 --> 00:41:25.590
We have this really
exciting farm there.

00:41:25.590 --> 00:41:27.360
We're going to have
coffee from this farm

00:41:27.360 --> 00:41:29.070
in just a couple of weeks.

00:41:29.070 --> 00:41:31.290
It's called Finca
Takesi and it lays

00:41:31.290 --> 00:41:34.000
the claim to being the highest
coffee farm in the world.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.787
And we've been buying coffee,
we bought coffee in 20 countries

00:41:36.787 --> 00:41:38.370
over the last 23
years and we've never

00:41:38.370 --> 00:41:39.570
found a higher coffee farm.

00:41:39.570 --> 00:41:44.247
So we have no evidence to
suggest the claim is untrue.

00:41:44.247 --> 00:41:46.080
So for me, I was going
to the highest coffee

00:41:46.080 --> 00:41:47.746
farm in the world, I
was really excited,

00:41:47.746 --> 00:41:49.350
my first trip to Bolivia.

00:41:49.350 --> 00:41:52.090
Bolivia's kind of a bit
of a backwater country

00:41:52.090 --> 00:41:53.721
as far as anything goes.

00:41:53.721 --> 00:41:55.470
It's landlocked, it's
very hard to get to,

00:41:55.470 --> 00:41:58.320
all the flights
arrive at 3:00 AM.

00:41:58.320 --> 00:42:00.390
I wanted to save the
company a couple of nickels,

00:42:00.390 --> 00:42:02.520
and I had a complicated
itinerary that

00:42:02.520 --> 00:42:04.450
had two stops instead of one.

00:42:04.450 --> 00:42:06.570
And I went to the first
stop on the first day

00:42:06.570 --> 00:42:08.570
and I missed my connection,
I had to wait a day,

00:42:08.570 --> 00:42:09.944
so I spent a night in Guatemala.

00:42:09.944 --> 00:42:11.610
And then I went the
next day to Colombia

00:42:11.610 --> 00:42:12.505
and I missed my
connection there,

00:42:12.505 --> 00:42:13.515
so I had to spend a
night in Colombia.

00:42:13.515 --> 00:42:15.540
So on the third day
after leaving Chicago,

00:42:15.540 --> 00:42:18.770
I pull in at 3:00 AM
to La Paz in Bolivia.

00:42:18.770 --> 00:42:21.120
And my partner picks us up
and we head out to the field,

00:42:21.120 --> 00:42:23.130
and we're about 10
minutes from the farm,

00:42:23.130 --> 00:42:27.060
and in the Bolivian Andes,
these commanding Bolivian Andes.

00:42:27.060 --> 00:42:29.925
And the car flipped and
rolled over once, twice,

00:42:29.925 --> 00:42:32.010
three, five or six times.

00:42:32.010 --> 00:42:33.900
And we dropped about
100 meters down the side

00:42:33.900 --> 00:42:36.110
of one of these big mountains.

00:42:36.110 --> 00:42:40.170
And by some sort of miracle,
we both emerged unscathed.

00:42:40.170 --> 00:42:42.000
But I had had enough.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:43.530
I was mentally a
little bit taxed,

00:42:43.530 --> 00:42:44.904
so I got on the
next flight home.

00:42:44.904 --> 00:42:47.430
So I spent five days
on a sourcing trip,

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:49.320
and I spent about 13
minutes on a farm,

00:42:49.320 --> 00:42:52.050
and then I was evacuated to
go to a hospital [INAUDIBLE]..

00:42:52.050 --> 00:42:53.670
All that hard
planning, it doesn't--

00:42:53.670 --> 00:42:56.160
careful planning doesn't
always lead to success.

00:42:56.160 --> 00:42:59.370
But I was just there
last month, no incidents.

00:42:59.370 --> 00:43:01.680
The coffee is beautiful
and delicious.

00:43:01.680 --> 00:43:05.132
One of the things we
do at our ECW event,

00:43:05.132 --> 00:43:07.590
is the last two years we've
had a coffee competition, which

00:43:07.590 --> 00:43:08.256
is just awesome.

00:43:08.256 --> 00:43:11.880
So think about the all-star team
of coffee, everybody bringing

00:43:11.880 --> 00:43:14.970
the best two kilos of coffee
they can produce to the table.

00:43:14.970 --> 00:43:17.640
Sam roasts it, we all
cup it, we qualify it,

00:43:17.640 --> 00:43:19.830
and then the growers
themselves vote.

00:43:19.830 --> 00:43:22.360
We have awards that are voted
on by everybody in the supply

00:43:22.360 --> 00:43:22.860
chain.

00:43:22.860 --> 00:43:24.526
So they're tasting
each other's coffees,

00:43:24.526 --> 00:43:26.990
they're looking around the
room, they're all blindly coded.

00:43:26.990 --> 00:43:29.040
So people are going, is
this mine, is that hers,

00:43:29.040 --> 00:43:30.630
is it his, whose is it?

00:43:30.630 --> 00:43:31.970
And then we reveal the coffees.

00:43:31.970 --> 00:43:35.700
So this coffee from this farm
was voted the best coffee

00:43:35.700 --> 00:43:38.720
in the southern hemisphere,
best coffee in South America,

00:43:38.720 --> 00:43:41.160
and we've got two bags of this
coffee that are coming in,

00:43:41.160 --> 00:43:43.800
two 60 kilo bags that are coming
in in a couple of weeks' time.

00:43:43.800 --> 00:43:45.400
So we'll make a
big deal about it

00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:47.400
when it arrives, and it's
going to be delicious.

00:43:47.400 --> 00:43:49.899
So in the end, it will
all have been worth it.

00:43:49.899 --> 00:43:50.940
JOHN PETRENKO: Very cool.

00:43:50.940 --> 00:43:51.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:51.440 --> 00:43:54.090
Well, I think we
are about time for--

00:43:54.090 --> 00:43:56.790
to open up to a
Q&amp;A. So if anybody

00:43:56.790 --> 00:43:58.590
wants to ask a
question, we'll have

00:43:58.590 --> 00:44:01.560
a microphone running around.

00:44:01.560 --> 00:44:03.600
AUDIENCE: So you
mentioned the three waves.

00:44:03.600 --> 00:44:06.550
What do you think is wave
number four if it comes?

00:44:06.550 --> 00:44:09.780
And what's the future of
both coffee production,

00:44:09.780 --> 00:44:12.266
to your earlier question,
and coffee consumption?

00:44:16.550 --> 00:44:20.120
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: Well I'll
start and you guys can jump in.

00:44:20.120 --> 00:44:22.150
I think we're going
to continue to see--

00:44:22.150 --> 00:44:23.150
on the production side--

00:44:23.150 --> 00:44:26.630
I think we're going to continue
to see a segregation of farms.

00:44:29.360 --> 00:44:32.030
On the commodity side,
what you're seeing across

00:44:32.030 --> 00:44:37.250
the world is this move to
massive, massive farms,

00:44:37.250 --> 00:44:41.690
primarily in Brazil
and Vietnam where

00:44:41.690 --> 00:44:45.680
all of the work on the farm
is being done mechanically.

00:44:45.680 --> 00:44:49.340
And so that, I think,
will continue to grow.

00:44:49.340 --> 00:44:52.070
Those farms are
becoming so efficient

00:44:52.070 --> 00:44:54.770
that they can make
money even when

00:44:54.770 --> 00:44:57.260
the commodity market is at $1.

00:44:57.260 --> 00:45:01.280
Most farms-- I don't
know if you have a stat,

00:45:01.280 --> 00:45:02.570
for some reason I want--

00:45:02.570 --> 00:45:02.800
I think it's like--

00:45:02.800 --> 00:45:03.300
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: $1.40, $1.50.

00:45:03.300 --> 00:45:05.716
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: Yeah. $1.40,
$1.50 is kind of break even

00:45:05.716 --> 00:45:07.010
for most farmers.

00:45:07.010 --> 00:45:08.990
And so I think you're
going to continue

00:45:08.990 --> 00:45:14.990
to see that agribusiness
grow for the commodity side.

00:45:14.990 --> 00:45:17.370
On the specialty side--

00:45:17.370 --> 00:45:22.870
and so that model is
not sustainable for most

00:45:22.870 --> 00:45:24.342
smallholders.

00:45:24.342 --> 00:45:26.050
The smallholder is
never going to compete

00:45:26.050 --> 00:45:27.640
with the massive
farm in Brazil that

00:45:27.640 --> 00:45:29.740
has huge tractors,
and everything else,

00:45:29.740 --> 00:45:31.700
and all this money behind it.

00:45:31.700 --> 00:45:35.380
So the only hope, in my
opinion, for the smallholder

00:45:35.380 --> 00:45:39.370
is to focus on quality and
go the route of specialty.

00:45:39.370 --> 00:45:41.860
That requires an investment,
it requires time, it's

00:45:41.860 --> 00:45:44.711
not something that you
just turn on overnight.

00:45:44.711 --> 00:45:46.960
But I don't think there's
going to be a middle ground.

00:45:46.960 --> 00:45:49.090
Either you're doing
specialty coffee,

00:45:49.090 --> 00:45:50.950
or you're in the
commodity world.

00:45:50.950 --> 00:45:53.350
I just don't see a future
for the smallholder trying

00:45:53.350 --> 00:45:56.990
to produce commodity coffee.

00:45:56.990 --> 00:46:01.960
I kind of alluded to
this earlier, I believe--

00:46:01.960 --> 00:46:03.970
there's so much more
complexity in coffee

00:46:03.970 --> 00:46:05.980
than we currently understand.

00:46:05.980 --> 00:46:09.320
There's varietals,
there's processing method,

00:46:09.320 --> 00:46:12.160
there's the stuff that
Sam does with the roaster.

00:46:12.160 --> 00:46:17.500
And the average consumer
still doesn't get it.

00:46:17.500 --> 00:46:21.332
There's so much more for us
to unlock for the consumer.

00:46:21.332 --> 00:46:23.290
And it's something that
we talk a lot about, is

00:46:23.290 --> 00:46:26.050
how do we communicate
the complexity of coffee,

00:46:26.050 --> 00:46:27.790
and how do we do
it in a way that

00:46:27.790 --> 00:46:31.270
doesn't overwhelm the consumer?

00:46:31.270 --> 00:46:33.520
And I don't know that we've
totally figured it out.

00:46:33.520 --> 00:46:37.210
We're trying, but I think
over the next 5 to 10 years,

00:46:37.210 --> 00:46:39.730
coffee is going to continue
to go the route of wine,

00:46:39.730 --> 00:46:43.510
where consumers
start to say, wow, I

00:46:43.510 --> 00:46:47.620
really like the Catuai variety
processed in a washed method,

00:46:47.620 --> 00:46:51.327
or a pulp natural method,
and I really like Costa Rica.

00:46:51.327 --> 00:46:53.410
One of the things-- one
of the concepts that we've

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:56.455
introduced at Intelligentsia
is this idea of seasonality.

00:46:56.455 --> 00:46:58.330
And so if you go into
one of our coffee bars,

00:46:58.330 --> 00:47:02.140
you'll see a sticker that says,
some bags say it's in season.

00:47:02.140 --> 00:47:05.140
And the reason we do that is
because what we have found

00:47:05.140 --> 00:47:08.200
is that one of the most
important factors to freshness

00:47:08.200 --> 00:47:11.524
and taste is the number
of days off of harvest.

00:47:11.524 --> 00:47:12.940
Everyone always
talks about roast,

00:47:12.940 --> 00:47:14.398
and roast date is
really important.

00:47:14.398 --> 00:47:17.680
Eh, it is, but I
think we're missing

00:47:17.680 --> 00:47:20.470
a huge part of it,
which is how old is it,

00:47:20.470 --> 00:47:23.050
how many days off of
the harvest is it?

00:47:23.050 --> 00:47:26.197
And so there's really two
buying seasons in the world.

00:47:26.197 --> 00:47:28.030
There's coffee from the
northern hemisphere,

00:47:28.030 --> 00:47:30.400
it all harvests at more
or less the same time.

00:47:30.400 --> 00:47:32.800
And countries in the southern
hemisphere, more or less

00:47:32.800 --> 00:47:34.310
harvest at the same time.

00:47:34.310 --> 00:47:38.620
And so we use as a rule, nine
months off of harvest, that's

00:47:38.620 --> 00:47:39.880
considered in season for us.

00:47:39.880 --> 00:47:41.380
And that's really
where you're going

00:47:41.380 --> 00:47:43.172
to get the peak of
flavors and freshness.

00:47:43.172 --> 00:47:44.380
And I use that as an example.

00:47:44.380 --> 00:47:45.460
I mean, that's just--

00:47:45.460 --> 00:47:47.835
again, we're just scratching
the surface with this stuff.

00:47:47.835 --> 00:47:50.090
There's so much more
complexity-- as you know--

00:47:50.090 --> 00:47:51.130
to coffee.

00:47:51.130 --> 00:47:53.440
And we as an industry,
I think, have

00:47:53.440 --> 00:47:56.330
to continue to push
consumers to understand,

00:47:56.330 --> 00:48:00.550
hey, there's all these different
variables that affect flavor,

00:48:00.550 --> 00:48:04.510
and we need to educate consumers
around what coffees they like,

00:48:04.510 --> 00:48:09.400
and then take them on a journey
in their coffee life, you know?

00:48:09.400 --> 00:48:12.790
If you really like the pulp
natural from Brazil, that's

00:48:12.790 --> 00:48:15.760
great, we're going to kind
of introduce you there,

00:48:15.760 --> 00:48:17.410
then we might take
you to Peru, then we

00:48:17.410 --> 00:48:19.034
might take you to
Honduras, and then we

00:48:19.034 --> 00:48:21.070
might take you to East Africa.

00:48:21.070 --> 00:48:24.670
There's really, I think, an
evolution in most consumers

00:48:24.670 --> 00:48:27.057
coffee journeys, their lives.

00:48:27.057 --> 00:48:27.991
[INAUDIBLE]

00:48:27.991 --> 00:48:30.550
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: Yeah, I mean,
I see both of those things.

00:48:30.550 --> 00:48:35.950
I think at origin, there's going
to be a consolidation where

00:48:35.950 --> 00:48:38.680
we have fewer and fewer growers
of small-- fewer and fewer

00:48:38.680 --> 00:48:40.180
smallholder growers.

00:48:40.180 --> 00:48:42.880
And I think that we're going
to get this really bifurcated

00:48:42.880 --> 00:48:47.500
market with commodity growers,
and then craft growers,

00:48:47.500 --> 00:48:49.990
really hyper focused on
quality and incorporating more

00:48:49.990 --> 00:48:52.589
technology and more precision.

00:48:52.589 --> 00:48:54.130
In the marketplace
side, I'm not sure

00:48:54.130 --> 00:48:56.470
if it's what I
believe will happen

00:48:56.470 --> 00:48:57.804
or what I just hope will happen.

00:48:57.804 --> 00:48:59.220
AUDIENCE: I'll
take it either way.

00:48:59.220 --> 00:48:59.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:59.800 --> 00:49:02.300
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: One of
the things that has been,

00:49:02.300 --> 00:49:06.280
frankly, a little frustrating
for specialty coffee people,

00:49:06.280 --> 00:49:08.900
James has talked about this idea
of coffee is culinary for us

00:49:08.900 --> 00:49:09.920
as a core belief.

00:49:09.920 --> 00:49:12.530
But when I meet
people who don't know

00:49:12.530 --> 00:49:17.927
what Intelligentsia is, well
my first thing is say, what?

00:49:17.927 --> 00:49:19.510
You don't know what
Intelligentsia is?

00:49:19.510 --> 00:49:22.000
But I try to explain it to
people, like family members who

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:23.710
don't know what I
do, I say, well, it's

00:49:23.710 --> 00:49:25.960
like a farm to table
restaurant for coffee.

00:49:25.960 --> 00:49:27.907
And I think so much of
what's exciting about--

00:49:27.907 --> 00:49:29.740
and has been exciting
about our food culture

00:49:29.740 --> 00:49:32.760
over the last 10 or
20 years, the idea

00:49:32.760 --> 00:49:34.480
that James mentioned
of seasonality,

00:49:34.480 --> 00:49:38.440
of relentless search for
flavor, local ingredients,

00:49:38.440 --> 00:49:40.360
fresh ingredients.

00:49:40.360 --> 00:49:43.180
All of those things that make
our food culture so exciting

00:49:43.180 --> 00:49:45.550
are really fundamental to
the way we source coffee

00:49:45.550 --> 00:49:48.470
and the way we try to position
coffee in the marketplace.

00:49:48.470 --> 00:49:51.064
And I feel like there has
been-- coffee hasn't--

00:49:51.064 --> 00:49:53.230
we see ourselves very much
as part of that movement.

00:49:53.230 --> 00:49:58.180
And in some senses, the work
that we've done in our sourcing

00:49:58.180 --> 00:50:01.630
predates a lot of the work
that's been done in food.

00:50:01.630 --> 00:50:04.120
But we haven't been
mapped into that.

00:50:04.120 --> 00:50:06.820
And so we talk a lot
about wine in coffee,

00:50:06.820 --> 00:50:09.022
and I think it's
probably a case of envy,

00:50:09.022 --> 00:50:10.480
where we want to
be more like wine.

00:50:10.480 --> 00:50:12.850
But we think it's
instructive and it's

00:50:12.850 --> 00:50:14.320
important in a lot of ways.

00:50:14.320 --> 00:50:16.600
Chemically, coffee is
more complex than wine.

00:50:16.600 --> 00:50:19.355
It has the same kind of things
that you think about wine.

00:50:19.355 --> 00:50:22.490
A vintage, well every
year, Finca Takesi

00:50:22.490 --> 00:50:23.870
produces a Geisha
varietal that's

00:50:23.870 --> 00:50:25.620
somewhat different
from the previous year.

00:50:25.620 --> 00:50:27.161
And it depends on
all the things that

00:50:27.161 --> 00:50:28.870
affect the vintages of wine.

00:50:28.870 --> 00:50:30.870
So there's a lot of really
good analogies there.

00:50:30.870 --> 00:50:33.360
And I think coffee--

00:50:33.360 --> 00:50:35.190
to James's point about
coffee's complexity

00:50:35.190 --> 00:50:38.040
being under-appreciated,
we feel like coffee's time

00:50:38.040 --> 00:50:39.720
is coming in terms
of being really

00:50:39.720 --> 00:50:42.560
appreciated as the culinary
product that it is.

00:50:42.560 --> 00:50:46.230
And as James said, we're
also searching for our role,

00:50:46.230 --> 00:50:48.960
and trying to help people
appreciate that, and help

00:50:48.960 --> 00:50:52.594
move specialty to that moment.

00:50:52.594 --> 00:50:53.760
I hope that's in our future.

00:50:53.760 --> 00:50:55.902
JOHN PETRENKO: Yeah, definitely

00:50:55.902 --> 00:50:57.360
AUDIENCE: So with
the wine analogy,

00:50:57.360 --> 00:51:00.810
I was kind of thinking about
when coffee has its "Sideways"

00:51:00.810 --> 00:51:03.490
moment, you know, how
that movie came out.

00:51:03.490 --> 00:51:05.320
But no, my question
is more about--

00:51:05.320 --> 00:51:07.560
the thing I've sort
of noticed and have

00:51:07.560 --> 00:51:09.320
commented when I-- so
I live in Lake View,

00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:10.804
and I go to Lake View Cafe.

00:51:10.804 --> 00:51:11.970
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: Thank you.

00:51:11.970 --> 00:51:13.719
AUDIENCE: I noticed
[INAUDIBLE] I love it.

00:51:13.719 --> 00:51:19.020
And I feel a lot more like
it's an experiential thing when

00:51:19.020 --> 00:51:19.567
I go there.

00:51:19.567 --> 00:51:21.900
Like it feels much more
curated, not just the selection,

00:51:21.900 --> 00:51:23.560
but also--

00:51:23.560 --> 00:51:26.310
I feel myself approaching
it a little differently.

00:51:26.310 --> 00:51:28.370
And I have a spouse
who steadfastly

00:51:28.370 --> 00:51:29.370
refuses to drink coffee.

00:51:29.370 --> 00:51:30.000
He won't touch it.

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:31.710
It frustrates the hell out
of me because I'm like,

00:51:31.710 --> 00:51:33.585
there's so many things
you're missing, right?

00:51:33.585 --> 00:51:35.400
And then I also have
friends who are like,

00:51:35.400 --> 00:51:37.110
I go to Dunkin' Donuts
and get a buzz on.

00:51:37.110 --> 00:51:41.829
And so, how does that spectrum--

00:51:41.829 --> 00:51:43.620
how do I make my friends
into coffee snobs?

00:51:43.620 --> 00:51:46.680
No, how do you view
the experiential bent

00:51:46.680 --> 00:51:48.780
that Intelligentsia
occupies as sort

00:51:48.780 --> 00:51:50.280
of that niche in the market?

00:51:50.280 --> 00:51:52.440
And how do you
expand that if you're

00:51:52.440 --> 00:51:54.540
talking about complexity
when a lot of people

00:51:54.540 --> 00:51:55.740
don't necessarily notice it?

00:51:55.740 --> 00:51:57.390
Is there like a
"Sideways" moment that you

00:51:57.390 --> 00:51:58.431
think the industry needs?

00:51:58.431 --> 00:51:59.880
Are you driving that?

00:51:59.880 --> 00:52:01.560
Is the supplier driving that?

00:52:01.560 --> 00:52:03.840
Are small neighborhood
places going to drive that?

00:52:03.840 --> 00:52:05.850
How do you see that happening?

00:52:05.850 --> 00:52:07.110
JAMES MCLAUGHLIN: Yeah.

00:52:07.110 --> 00:52:11.492
I think to answer at least
part of your question,

00:52:11.492 --> 00:52:13.200
we have this belief
that coffee should be

00:52:13.200 --> 00:52:14.890
treated as a culinary product.

00:52:14.890 --> 00:52:23.700
And so if we emulated the
traditional fast food model,

00:52:23.700 --> 00:52:27.160
I don't think we could have
gotten to where we have today.

00:52:27.160 --> 00:52:31.380
And so part of it is, we have
to do something different

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:33.730
for customers to
come in and say,

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:36.151
yeah, I'm OK paying $6
for a black cup of coffee

00:52:36.151 --> 00:52:38.400
even though I can go down
the street to Dunkin' Donuts

00:52:38.400 --> 00:52:39.165
and get it for $2.

00:52:42.730 --> 00:52:47.110
So having an experience,
a complete experience

00:52:47.110 --> 00:52:49.840
for customers I think is really
important for us as a brand.

00:52:52.890 --> 00:52:55.290
We don't have an
interest in having

00:52:55.290 --> 00:52:58.350
5,000 Intelligentsias
around Chicago,

00:52:58.350 --> 00:52:59.790
or around the United States.

00:52:59.790 --> 00:53:02.010
We want to keep
this pretty boutique

00:53:02.010 --> 00:53:08.630
and grow the brand through
the coffee bar experience,

00:53:08.630 --> 00:53:11.010
but then it's available in
a lot of different places,

00:53:11.010 --> 00:53:17.720
at your Whole Foods, at your
office, wherever it may be.

00:53:17.720 --> 00:53:20.300
But one thing that
we struggle with

00:53:20.300 --> 00:53:24.260
is, not everyone wants to wait
six minutes for a pour over.

00:53:24.260 --> 00:53:28.412
And particularly at our downtown
locations, it's something

00:53:28.412 --> 00:53:29.870
that we talk about
a lot, how do we

00:53:29.870 --> 00:53:32.900
meet customers where they
want a great cup of coffee,

00:53:32.900 --> 00:53:35.420
they're not willing
to wait six minutes?

00:53:35.420 --> 00:53:38.750
And it's something that,
candidly, we struggle with.

00:53:38.750 --> 00:53:42.590
Because we don't want it
to become fast foodie,

00:53:42.590 --> 00:53:46.340
right, like too much like a fast
food experience, because then

00:53:46.340 --> 00:53:48.570
we lose the credibility
around, hey,

00:53:48.570 --> 00:53:51.060
this is a culinary experience.

00:53:51.060 --> 00:53:53.737
But at the same time,
if there's customers

00:53:53.737 --> 00:53:55.820
that want to come in and
get a great cup of coffee

00:53:55.820 --> 00:53:58.620
but get it quickly, we
want to serve them too.

00:53:58.620 --> 00:54:02.090
And I think one of
the things that we--

00:54:02.090 --> 00:54:04.220
one of the cool parts of
getting to design a coffee

00:54:04.220 --> 00:54:08.159
bar every time we open one,
it's both maddening and cool

00:54:08.159 --> 00:54:10.700
because it's like, OK, we've
got to start from scratch again,

00:54:10.700 --> 00:54:12.660
we don't have this
cookie cutter template.

00:54:12.660 --> 00:54:15.020
But we do get to experiment
with service models.

00:54:15.020 --> 00:54:17.090
And so I'll give you an example.

00:54:17.090 --> 00:54:19.730
Like our Logan Square
shop here in Chicago,

00:54:19.730 --> 00:54:21.710
a barista comes over,
you sit at the bar,

00:54:21.710 --> 00:54:24.890
the barista will wait
on you, you can engage.

00:54:24.890 --> 00:54:27.500
The baristas will kind
of read the customer

00:54:27.500 --> 00:54:29.510
and try to figure out
how much they want

00:54:29.510 --> 00:54:31.010
to engage about the coffee.

00:54:31.010 --> 00:54:32.270
Like, do they want to
talk about the coffee

00:54:32.270 --> 00:54:33.395
or are they just here for--

00:54:33.395 --> 00:54:37.160
you know, they just want the cup
of coffee and leave me alone,

00:54:37.160 --> 00:54:39.020
I just woke up.

00:54:39.020 --> 00:54:40.190
So there's that experience.

00:54:40.190 --> 00:54:42.396
But then you can also
at the front of the bar,

00:54:42.396 --> 00:54:43.520
you can get a coffee to go.

00:54:43.520 --> 00:54:45.450
And it should be a
faster experience.

00:54:45.450 --> 00:54:49.760
And so I can't say that
we've cracked that nut,

00:54:49.760 --> 00:54:52.040
but it's definitely
something that we're still

00:54:52.040 --> 00:54:54.680
trying to figure out.

00:54:54.680 --> 00:54:55.679
Because I want to--

00:54:55.679 --> 00:54:57.470
I mean, one of the
things we all want to do

00:54:57.470 --> 00:55:01.310
is introduce more people,
your wife, your friends

00:55:01.310 --> 00:55:02.600
to this cup of coffee.

00:55:02.600 --> 00:55:05.330
Because I think once you
try it, you're hooked,

00:55:05.330 --> 00:55:08.270
and it's hard to go back
to the Dunkin' Donuts.

00:55:08.270 --> 00:55:12.190
MICHAEL SHERIDAN: I think also,
it should be said that we--

00:55:12.190 --> 00:55:15.620
our obsession with quality, we
have a lighter roast profile

00:55:15.620 --> 00:55:17.450
than most.

00:55:17.450 --> 00:55:19.460
And that really is
not by accident.

00:55:19.460 --> 00:55:23.420
I mean, it's a reflection
of the quality of the coffee

00:55:23.420 --> 00:55:25.610
that we source.

00:55:25.610 --> 00:55:27.710
One of my colleagues
recently put it so well,

00:55:27.710 --> 00:55:30.470
I think, for a
non-coffee person.

00:55:30.470 --> 00:55:34.610
He was saying that, if you get
a beautiful piece of tuna that's

00:55:34.610 --> 00:55:36.860
sushi grade, you don't
even have to cook it,

00:55:36.860 --> 00:55:38.760
you can just eat it.

00:55:38.760 --> 00:55:42.170
But if you get an old piece of
tuna that's not the best cut,

00:55:42.170 --> 00:55:44.850
you got to cook it for a long
time to make it palatable.

00:55:44.850 --> 00:55:46.520
And it's sort of like
that with coffee.

00:55:46.520 --> 00:55:49.020
We're sourcing some of
the world's finest coffee.

00:55:49.020 --> 00:55:53.480
You don't need to layer on all
of that caramelization and all

00:55:53.480 --> 00:55:56.390
that bitterness that you
get in the deep, dark roast.

00:55:56.390 --> 00:55:58.730
You can create something
really beautiful by letting

00:55:58.730 --> 00:56:02.180
your foot off the gas and
letting it breathe at a lighter

00:56:02.180 --> 00:56:03.590
roast profile.

00:56:03.590 --> 00:56:09.890
So we tend to regard the
really dark carbonized coffee

00:56:09.890 --> 00:56:12.190
as not culinary.

00:56:12.190 --> 00:56:14.960
You know, you're not
tasting the terroir,

00:56:14.960 --> 00:56:16.760
you're not tasting the
work, you're tasting

00:56:16.760 --> 00:56:19.280
the hand of the roaster.

00:56:19.280 --> 00:56:22.550
And so, you know,
most of us who are

00:56:22.550 --> 00:56:25.064
coffee professionals
in Intelligentsia,

00:56:25.064 --> 00:56:26.480
we don't reach for
the dark roast.

00:56:26.480 --> 00:56:29.510
But even our dark roast, we
try to reimagine the dark roast

00:56:29.510 --> 00:56:31.670
for a kind of a
specialty audience.

00:56:31.670 --> 00:56:36.950
So our dark roast, if you
put it next to a brand who

00:56:36.950 --> 00:56:41.690
shall not be mentioned, they're
occupying different planets.

00:56:41.690 --> 00:56:44.817
And so I think to your point,
meeting people where they are,

00:56:44.817 --> 00:56:46.400
and this idea of a
journey, and trying

00:56:46.400 --> 00:56:48.980
to help people
discover coffee, we

00:56:48.980 --> 00:56:52.120
want to have a dark roast
that's, hey, try this,

00:56:52.120 --> 00:56:53.300
reimagine your dark roast.

00:56:53.300 --> 00:56:56.060
It doesn't have to
taste like an ashtray.

00:56:56.060 --> 00:56:58.264
There's some nuance there,
there's some citrus,

00:56:58.264 --> 00:56:59.930
there's some sweetness,
but you're still

00:56:59.930 --> 00:57:04.580
getting that slight little
bite, and something that you go,

00:57:04.580 --> 00:57:06.740
oh, this is a different
kind of thing.

00:57:06.740 --> 00:57:09.560
And I think it should be said
as I look at three different tap

00:57:09.560 --> 00:57:12.260
systems in the back of the room,
part of the future of coffee

00:57:12.260 --> 00:57:15.190
is coffee as an ingredient,
and coffee as an ingredient

00:57:15.190 --> 00:57:18.120
in the broader beverage market.

00:57:18.120 --> 00:57:21.241
And so I think we can
look down our nose at some

00:57:21.241 --> 00:57:22.740
of those things,
or we can say, hey,

00:57:22.740 --> 00:57:24.890
this is an opportunity to
engage people and meet them

00:57:24.890 --> 00:57:26.810
where they are and where
they're having coffee

00:57:26.810 --> 00:57:28.820
with a product that's superior.

00:57:28.820 --> 00:57:30.987
And try to bring
them into a deeper

00:57:30.987 --> 00:57:33.320
appreciation for everything
that companies like ours do.

00:57:33.320 --> 00:57:34.000
JOHN PETRENKO: Very cool.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:35.960
SAM SABORI: Yeah, I think
that that "Sideways"

00:57:35.960 --> 00:57:38.090
